neonatal adverse events during maternal pharmacotherapy. A cost-effectiveness
analysis, using a decision model, was performed with a hypothetical cohort of
prenatal subjects. Parameter estimates, costs and ranges for sensitivity analyses
were ascertained from the literature and expert opinion. Sensitivity analyses
were conducted to assess the robustness of the results. Probabilistic sensitivity
analysis revealed an incremental cost-effectiveness (ICER) of {\$}10 433 (Canadian
